Appletters is a fun and smart word building game. It is the new domino game you don't connect the dots you connect the letters. Create a continuous word snake by adding your word to the head or tail. As you add new words to the head and tail, the snake gets longer and the game gets harder! But stay on your toes: as the snake twists and turns, your aim stays the same: be the first to use all your tiles – and win! The apple shaped pouch with a soft, zip-closed top includes 110 tiles with red capital letters that may be used to play three different games:  Appleletters: Players alternately add tiles to the first or last letter of a word in the middle of the table creating a continuous snake of new words.  Apple Turnover: Similar to Appleletters, however each player begins with 21 tiles instead of nine, and may actually replace an opponent's word with a longer word. The goal is to be the first player to get rid of tiles.  Applescore: Players build words as long as possible in crossword-like fashion and get bonus points for length, palindromes and going out first. For two to four players, ages 7 and up.

Zip-It is a fast-paced word game that you can play anywhere. All of the game pieces (24 letter cubes and instructions) fit inside the cloth pouch, and the pouch itself serves as the scorekeeping mechanism. One player is the yellow zipper, and the other player is the green zipper. As you score points, move your zipper up according to the numbers on the side of the pouch. If you're the first to zip to the top, you win.  Each player takes 12 letter cubes, and at the same time, both players start to form their own intersecting word grid (kind of like what a crossword looks like) using any side of their cubes. The first player to complete a grid with no remaining cubes yells “Zip!” As long as that player's grid was correctly completed (no proper nouns, no abbreviations, no misspelled or non-existent words), that player moves their zipper up one spot. Continue playing rounds in the same way until one player has won 10 rounds.

Jacquards are part of the heritage almost as much as nylon. They're unique fabrics: highly-textured, with patterns that are woven, instead of printed. For this collection Kate Spade wanted to do something totally new with the signature spade flower pattern. Kate Spade looked to Limonta, a centuries-old, family-owned textile mill in northern Italy near Como. They’ve been producing and experimenting with jacquards for over 100 years, and are one of the world’s most renowned mills. Together Kate Spade has made something special. Jacquards are part of our heritage almost as much as nylon. They're unique fabrics: highly-textured, with patterns that are woven, instead of printed. for this collection we wanted to do something totally new with our signature spade flower pattern. We looked to Limonta, a centuries-old, family-owned textile mill in northern Italy near Como. They’ve been producing and experimenting with jacquards for over 100 years, and are one of the world’s most renowned mills. Together we've made something special. Here, we've used our new Spade Flower Jacquard (topped with stripes, another element reimagined from our archives) on our Manhattan small tote--a compact bag for all the little things.
